	<body>
		<div class="container">
			<header>
				<h1>Hick's Law</h1>
			</header>
			<nav>
				<p>
					<h2>Bad Example</h2>
					<ul class="bad_example">
						<li>First Page</li>
						<li>Second Page</li>
						<li>Middle Page</li>
						<li>Second to last Page</li>
						<li>Last Page</li>
					</ul>
				</p>

				<p>
					<h2>Good Example</h2>
					<ul class="good_example">
						<li>Previous Page</li>
						<li>Next Page</li>
				</p>
				<p> This is a good example of Hick's Law. Hick's Law says you should always reduce
					the number of choices the user has. When you get to the bottom of the page
					the last thing you want is to have multiple options of how to get to different
					pages when sorting through a document.
				</p>

			</nav>

		</div>
	</body>
</html>
